Rate of change of longitudinal strain over time.

RadialLagrangianStrain:
Lagrangian strain in the wall of a cavity perpendicular to the longitudinal strain and towards the center of the cavity.

RadialLagrangianStrainRate:
Rate of change of radial Lagrangian strain over time.

CircumferentialLagrangianStrain:
Lagrangian strain tangential to the reference contour, perpendicular to the longitudinal strain, with positive values in the counterclockwise direction when viewed from the apex.

CircumferentialLagrangianStrainRate:
Rate of change of circumferential Lagrangian strain over time.

2dSpeckleTracking:
A method of analyzing the motion of tissue, such as the heart muscle or blood, by using naturally occurring speckle patterns in 2D ultrasound imaging.

3dSpeckleTracking:
A method of analyzing the motion of tissue, such as the heart muscle or blood, by using naturally occurring speckle patterns in 3D ultrasound imaging.

ApicalFourChamberRvFocused:
A view obtained from the apical four chamber view by angling the beam medially toward the patients right shoulder to better include the right ventricle.
retired

ApicalFourChamberRvModified:
A view obtained from the apical four chamber view by angling the beam laterally toward the patients left shoulder to better include the right ventricle.
retired

EndocardialMethod:
A measurement method that uses a contour representing the estimated endocardial boundary.

EpicardialMethod:
A measurement method that uses a contour representing the estimated epicardial boundary.

MyocardialMidlayerMethod:
A measurement method that uses a contour representing the estimated mid-layer of the myocardium (between the endocardium and epicardium).

LvEnd-systolicGlsMultiviewMean(endocardial):
The longitudinal Lagrangian strain of the left ventricle calculated as the arithmetic mean of LV End-systolic Global Longitudinal Strain 4CH (Endocardial), LV End-systolic Global Longitudinal Strain 2CH (Endocardial), and LV End-systolic Global Longitudinal Strain ALAX (Endocardial).

LvEnd-systolicGls4ch(endocardial):
Sometimes abbreviated GLS4C.

LvEnd-systolicGls2ch(endocardial):
Sometimes abbreviated GLS2C.

LvEnd-systolicGlsAlax(endocardial):
Sometimes abbreviated GLSALAX.

concept.display: LV Peak Systolic GLS Multiview Mean (Endocardial)
concept.definition:
LvPeakSystolicGlsMultiviewMean(endocardial):
The peak longitudinal Lagrangian strain of the left ventricle calculated as the arithmetic mean of LV Peak Systolic Global Longitudinal Strain 4CH (Endocardial), LV Peak Systolic Global Longitudinal Strain 2CH (Endocardial), and LV Peak Systolic Global Longitudinal Strain ALAX (Endocardial).

LvPeakSystolicGls4ch(endocardial):
The measurement may have been taken at any point in the respiration cycle.

LvPeakSystolicGls2ch(endocardial):
The measurement may have been taken at any point in the respiration cycle.

LvPeakSystolicGlsAlax(endocardial):
The measurement may have been taken at any point in the respiration cycle.

LvPeakGlsMultiviewMean(endocardial):
The peak longitudinal Lagrangian strain of the left ventricle calculated as the arithmetic mean of LV Peak Global Longitudinal Strain 4CH (Endocardial), LV Peak Global Longitudinal Strain 2CH (Endocardial), and LV Peak Global Longitudinal Strain ALAX (Endocardial).

LvPeakGls4ch(endocardial):
The measurement may have been taken at any point in the respiration cycle.

LvPeakGls2ch(endocardial):
The measurement may have been taken at any point in the respiration cycle.

LvPeakGlsAlax(endocardial):
The measurement may have been taken at any point in the respiration cycle.

LvEnd-systolicMechanicalDispersion:
The measurement may have been taken using any view, using any segment model (16, 17 or 18-segment) and at any point in the respiration cycle.

MitralValveClosure:
The point in time in a cardiac cycle when the mitral valve nominally finishes closing.

MitralValveOpening:
The point in time in a cardiac cycle when the mitral valve nominally begins opening.

AorticValveClosure:
The point in time in a cardiac cycle when the aortic valve nominally finishes closing.

AorticValveOpening:
The point in time in a cardiac cycle when the aortic valve nominally begins opening.

Fp9:
EEG electrode placement on the head located inferior frontopolar, left.
retired

Fp10:
EEG electrode placement on the head located inferior frontopolar, right.
retired

Af9:
EEG electrode placement on the head located inferior anterior frontal, left.
retired

Af10:
EEG electrode placement on the head located inferior anterior frontal, right.
retired

Po9:
EEG electrode placement on the head located inferior parietooccipital, left.
retired

Po10:
EEG electrode placement on the head located inferior parietooccipital, right.
retired

O9:
EEG electrode placement on the head located inferior occipital, left.
retired

O10:
EEG electrode placement on the head located inferior occipital, right.
retired
CoronaryArteryDiseaseAssessment:
CoronaryArteryDiseaseAssessmentModifier:

concept.display: Coronary Artery Disease Stenosis Assessment Modifier
concept.definition: CoronaryArteryDiseaseStenosisAssessmentModifier:

0-DocumentedAbsenceOfCad:
Degree of maximal coronary stenosis is 0%.
retired

1-MinimalNon-obstructiveCad:
Degree of maximal coronary stenosis is 1-24%.
retired

2-MildNon-obstructiveCad:
Degree of maximal coronary stenosis is 25-49%.
retired

3-ModerateStenosis:
Degree of maximal coronary stenosis is 50-69%.
retired

4-SevereStenosis:
Degree of maximal coronary stenosis is 70-99%, or left main coronary stenosis is >50%, or coronary stenosis is >=70% in 3 vessels.
retired

4a-SevereStenosis:
Degree of maximal coronary stenosis is 70-99% stenosis.
retired

4b-SevereStenosis:
Left main coronary stenosis is >50% or coronary stenosis is >=70% in 3 vessels.
retired

5-TotalCoronaryOcclusion:
Degree of maximal coronary stenosis is 100% (total occlusion).
retired

N-Non-diagnosticStudy:
No more than mild coronary stenosis in interpretable segments, and one or more vessel segments non-diagnostic.
retired

N-Non-diagnosticSegments:
One or more vessel segments were non-diagnostic for coronary stenosis.
retired

S-Stent:
At least one coronary stent is present in the coronary system.
retired

G-Graft:
At least one coronary artery bypass graft is present.
retired

V-VulnerablePlaque:
Vulnerable plaque or high risk plaque features are present.
retired

TitaniumAlloy(titaniumMolybdenum-15Zirconium-5Aluminium-3):
Wrought titanium 15-molybdenum 5-zirconium 3-aluminium alloy.

RtSegmentMaterial:
Material identifiers used during or for an RT planning process.

DoseLimitInterlock:
An interlock triggered by reaching a predefined dose limit.

ClearanceInterlock:
An interlock triggered by the occurrence, or anticipation, of a physical collision caused by lack of separation distance between objects.

MachineClearanceInterlock:
An interlock triggered by the occurrence, or anticipation, of a physical collision caused by lack of separation distance between machine and machine.

PatientClearanceInterlock:
An interlock triggered by the occurrence, or anticipation, of a physical collision caused by lack of separation distance between machine and patient.

AccessoryClearanceInterlock:
An accessory can be e.g., an electron applicator or a stereotactic cone.

OutOfToleranceInterlock:
An interlock triggered by an actual value being outside of tolerance from the planned value.

InterlockResolved:
The interlock was resolved, and treatment delivery was continued.

CtDoseLengthProductSub-total:
The total dose length product for irradiation events within in the defined scope of accumulation that were computed using the same phantom.
retired

RtRegistrationMark:
Marker used in a registration process.

IsodoseVolume:
A volume whose surface represents an isodose.

RadiotherapyDoseRegion:
Region defined by the spatial extent of a radiation dose.

QualityControlMaterialImage:
Images that contain quality control material for the current procedure.

TissueNotOfInterest:
Tissue that is other than that which is of interest for the purpose of the task.
retired

DataNotAccessibleFromStorage:
Requested data cannot be read from storage media, e.g., data physically deleted, or storage media no longer available.

ProcessedKeyObjectSelection:
The SOP Instance is a Key Object Selection Document, used for referenced object change management, that has had its directives processed and is no longer to be used (see

ReplacedByAlternateRepresentation:
The SOP Instance has been replaced by a SOP Instance with an alternate encoding. The alternate encoding may utilize a different SOP Class or have different image quality characteristics (e.g., lossy compression).

ReferenceMeasurementGroup:
A grouping of related measurements and calculations that share a common context and that serves as a reference against which similar measurement groups are compared.

ParticleDisplacementMethod:
A method for detecting a shear wave in ultrasound data based on the displacement of particles relative to their referenced baseline positions.

ParticleVelocityMethod:
A method for detecting a shear wave in ultrasound data based on estimated particle velocity. Particle velocity is estimated from frame to frame particle displacement.

concept.display: Shear Wave Dispersion Slope Center Frequency
concept.definition:
ShearWaveDispersionSlopeCenterFrequency:
The center frequency of the range over which the shear wave dispersion slope was assessed.

ShearWaveDetectionMethod:
Method used to detect and characterize a shear wave motion signal in an ultrasound signal.

ButterworthFilter:
A signal processing filter of the Butterworth type.

ChebyshevFilter:
A signal processing filter of the Chebyshev type.

EllipticFilter:
An elliptic signal processing filter.

BesselFilter:
A signal processing filter of the Bessel type.

GaussianFilter:
A signal processing filter of the Gaussian type

K-typeFilter:
A K-type (constant k) signal processing filter.

M-derivedFilter:
An M-derived (m-type) signal processing filter.

Double-m-derivedFilter:
A double-m-derived (mm'-type) signal processing filter.

BodeFilter:
A signal processing filter of the Bode type.

ZobelFilter:
A signal processing filter of the Zobel type.

FirFilter:
A finite impulse response (FIR) signal processing filter.

CicFilter:
A cascaded integratorcomb (CIC) signal processing filter.

IirFilter:
An infinite impulse response (IIR) signal processing filter.

BiquadFilter:
A biquadratic signal processing filter (second order recursive linear filter).

HzNormalized:
Frequency in Hz divided by  of the sampling rate.

HzAngular:
Frequency in Hz divided by  of the sampling rate and then multiplied by  (pi).

MagnitudeNormalized:
Ratio of output magnitude to input magnitude, has no units and a value between 0-1.

SpecificObservationSubjectClass:
This is distinct from the Subject Class used in Observation Context, which more generally specifies the entire subject, usually the patient.

ImageFrame:
Usually used in the context of a multi-frame image.

concept.display: RT Patient Position Acquisition, Integrated Dose MV
concept.definition:
RtPatientPositionAcquisition,IntegratedDoseMv:
Acquisition of patient positioning information using continuous megavoltage acquisition during treatment delivery.

concept.display: RT Patient Position Acquisition, Film Cassette MV
concept.definition:
RtPatientPositionAcquisition,FilmCassetteMv:
Acquisition of patient positioning information using a radiation-sensitive film suited for megavoltage radiation.

concept.display: RT Patient Position Acquisition, Film Cassette kV
concept.definition:
RtPatientPositionAcquisition,FilmCassetteKv:
Acquisition of patient positioning information using a radiation-sensitive film suited for photon radiation.

concept.display: RT Patient Position Acquisition, Cone-Beam CT kV
concept.definition:
RtPatientPositionAcquisition,Cone-beamCtKv:
Acquisition of patient positioning information using kilovoltage Cone-Beam CT imaging.

concept.display: RT Patient Position Acquisition, Conventional CT kV
concept.definition:
RtPatientPositionAcquisition,ConventionalCtKv:
Acquisition of patient positioning information using kilovoltage conventional CT imaging.

concept.display: RT Patient Position Acquisition, Cone-Beam CT MV
concept.definition:
RtPatientPositionAcquisition,Cone-beamCtMv:
Acquisition of patient positioning information using megavoltage Cone-Beam CT imaging.

concept.display: RT Patient Position Acquisition, Conventional CT MV
concept.definition:
RtPatientPositionAcquisition,ConventionalCtMv:
Acquisition of patient positioning information using megavoltage conventional CT imaging.

NominalImagingSourceLocation:
The point location defined as the nominal source of radiation used for imaging.

RtPatientPositioningReferenceImage:
Image(s) of the patient used to provide a reference for positioning of the patient for the planned treatment.

AcquisitionInitiationType:
The type of method used to start the acquisition.

AcquisitionInitiationNotDefined:
The acquisition trigger is not specified. Acquisition may be initiated manually by the device operator.

concept.display: Acquisition Initiation before start of Radiation
concept.definition:
AcquisitionInitiationBeforeStartOfRadiation:
The acquisition is started before delivering the therapeutic radiation. It is expected that the therapeutic beam is not started before the acquisition is completed.

concept.display: Acquisition Initiation after end of Radiation
concept.definition:
AcquisitionInitiationAfterEndOfRadiation:
The acquisition is started after delivering the therapeutic radiation.

AcquisitionInitiationByTriggeringParameter:
The acquisition is started when the triggering parameter reaches specific value(s).

IncrementalAcquisitionTriggering:
Flag denoting whether the acquisition is to be repeated in regular intervals separated by a certain increment.

Meterset:
A single parameter from which the absorbed dose delivered can be calculated through a calibration procedure with additional information.

SourceContinuousRollAngle:
Angle in degrees about the Y-axis of the Equipment Coordinate System by which the source is rotated. A Continuous Rotation Angle is an angle in the range (-,+). Continuous Rotation Angle represent a rotation direction and magnitude. The magnitude is not limited to be between 0 and 360 degrees.

TimeAfterStartOfRadiation:
Time elapsed after the start of the delivery of an RT Radiation.

concept.display: Percentage of expected beam-on time of Radiation
concept.definition:
PercentageOfExpectedBeam-onTimeOfRadiation:
Delivered percentage of the duration of a Radiation at a given point in time. The denominator is the duration of time that the beam is expected to be on between the start and the end of the delivery of an RT Radiation. The numerator is the duration of time that the beam has been on since the start of the first beam-on. Both durations exclude beam-hold periods within the treatment delivery (e.g. during gated treatments).

concept.display: IEC61217 Imaging Source to Axis Distance
concept.definition:
Iec61217ImagingSourceToAxisDistance:
Distance from the imaging source, in mm, to the gantry rotation axis of a IEC C-Arm Device. This parameter is not specifically defined by

concept.display: IEC61217 X-Ray Image Receptor Radial Displacement from Isocenter
concept.definition:
Iec61217X-rayImageReceptorRadialDisplacementFromIsocenter:
X-Ray Image Receptor Radial Displacement From Isocenter, in mm (in the IEC GANTRY Coordinate System) as defined by

concept.display: IEC61217 X-Ray Image Receptor Longitudinal Displacement
concept.definition:
Iec61217X-rayImageReceptorLongitudinalDisplacement:
X-Ray Image Receptor Longitudinal Displacement, in mm (in the IEC GANTRY Coordinate System) as defined by

concept.display: IEC61217 X-Ray Image Receptor Lateral Displacement
concept.definition:
Iec61217X-rayImageReceptorLateralDisplacement:
X-Ray Image Receptor Lateral Displacement, in mm (in the IEC GANTRY Coordinate System) as defined by

Iec61217X-rayImageReceptorRotation:
X-Ray Image Receptor rotation (around the z-axis of the IEC X-RAY IMAGE RECEPTOR Coordinate System) as defined by

ConfiguredLowestImagingEnergy:
Lowest energy for acquiring an image as configured on the device.

ConfiguredDefaultImagingEnergy:
Default energy for acquiring an image as configured on the device.

PlanarMatrixUltrasoundTransducerGeometry:
Ultrasonic transducer geometry characterized by multiple transducer elements arranged in a grid on a plane.

HemisphericalUltrasoundTransducerGeometry:
Ultrasonic transducer geometry characterized by multiple transducer elements arranged on a hemispherical surface.

Single-sideIllumination:
The subject is illuminated from a single direction.

Dual-sideIllumination:
The subject is illuminated from two distinct directions.

Multi-sideIllumination:
The subject is illuminated from more than two (potentially a very large number of) distinct directions.

Through-transducerIllumination:
The subject is illuminated through the transducer. Light may pass through the transducer at one or more locations.

InterstitialIllumination:
The subject is illuminated internally. Light is delivered via a device (other than the transducer) inside the body.

PiezocompositeTransducer:
Ultrasound Transducer that utilizes Piezo-composite crystalline structures.

Mems-basedTransducer:
Ultrasound Transducer that utilizes Micro-electro-mechanical systems (MEMS)-based structures.

InterferometricTransducer:
Ultrasound Transducer that utilizes interferometric detection systems.

UniformSpeedOfSoundCorrection:
Mechanism for correction of data using a sound propagation model based on a single speed of sound, where the speed for the acoustic coupling medium (if present) is assumed to be the same as for the imaged object.

DualSpeedOfSoundCorrection:
Mechanism for correction of data using a sound propagation model based on two speeds of sound, one for the acoustic coupling medium and one for the imaged object.

SpeedOfSoundMapCorrection:
Mechanism for correction of data using a sound propagation model based on a speed of sound map that defines the speed of sound on a per-pixel basis.

SphericalBackProjection:
A family of algorithms for reconstructing an image from measured data by back-projection over spheres or parts of spheres. May include linear or nonlinear processing steps before and/or after the back-projection step. Includes methods termed beamforming and delay-and-sum.

NumericalAcousticModel:
A family of algorithms for reconstructing an image from measured data by iteratively adjusting the image to minimize a cost function between the data and a numerical model or that uses non-iterative (e.g. time-reversal) methods, or that performs inversion of a forward model matrix.

BloodDeoxygenationLevel:
Signal intensity of a Blood Deoxygenation Level image.

ScanSpotInterlock:
An interlock triggered during scan spot delivery that is not covered by a more specific code.

ScanSpotPositionInterlock:
An interlock triggered by the scan spot position being outside of tolerance.

ScanSpotSizeInterlock:
An interlock triggered by the scan spot size being outside of tolerance.

ScanSpotMetersetInterlock:
An interlock triggered by the Meterset delivered for a spot being outside of tolerance.

concept.display: Radiation Detected During Beam Hold Interlock
concept.definition:
RadiationDetectedDuringBeamHoldInterlock:
An interlock triggered by detection of radiation when the beam is supposed to be off.

MlcPositionInterlock:
An interlock triggered by a multileaf collimator (MLC) leaf position being outside of tolerance.

MetersetRateInterlock:
An interlock triggered by the detected Meterset rate being outside of tolerance.

BeamEnergyInterlock:
An interlock triggered by the detected energy of the beam being outside of tolerance.

SkinLesionColor:
A visual assessment of the coloration of a skin lesion.

Pre-surgicalAnatomy:
The anatomy of the subject prior to the effect of a surgical procedure.

SleepStageN1:
Non-REM Sleep Stage 1 is the transition between wakefulness and sleep.
retired

SleepStageN2:
Non-REM Sleep Stage 2 is light sleep.
retired

SleepStageN3:
Non-REM Sleep Stage 3 is deep sleep.
retired

SeatPanHeight:
The adjustable distance between the seat pan (the resting place for the patients bottom) and the nominal floor of the upright fixation device. Adjustment allows the feet to be placed firmly on the nominal floor without the legs being stretched or too cramped.

SeatPanPitchAngle:
The adjustable angle of the pitch of the seat pan. Adjustment provides thigh support while pitching downward changes the angle between the upper legs (knee to hip) and the abdomen. An angle of zero is a typical sitting position. A large positive angle, such as 75, puts a person in a nearly standing stance.

BackrestPitchAngle:
The adjustable angle of the pitch of the backrest. Adjustment controls the angle of the patients back (when in a nominally seated or upright position) with respect to gravity. Typically tilted back a bit so that the back is resting and slightly supported. An angle of zero means the backrest is vertical. A positive angle means the patient is reclining.

ShinRestPosition:
The adjustable distance between the shin rest and the nominal center under the seat of the chair. Adjustment accommodates the leg length and stance of the patient (the stance of the patient is adjusted primarily through the seat pan pitch angle and the backrest fixation pitch angle).

HeelStopPosition:
The adjustable distance between the heel stop and the shin rest. Adjustment accommodates the patient foot size, shin rest position, lower leg length, and the angle of the lower legs with respect to gravity. The zero point is device-specific.

LeftArmRestPosition:
The adjustable lateral distance between the left arm rest and patients thorax. The zero point is device-specific.

LeftArmRestPitchAngle:
The adjustable angle of the pitch of the left arm rest. Adjustment controls one of the angles of the elbow. An angle of zero means the arm rest is parallel to the ground.

LeftArmRestRollAngle:
The adjustable angle of the roll of the left arm rest. Adjustment controls the roll angle of the lower arm. An angle of zero means the arm rest is parallel to the ground.

RightArmRestPosition:
The adjustable lateral distance between the right arm rest and the patients thorax. The zero point is device-specific.

RightArmRestPitchAngle:
The adjustable angle of the pitch of the right arm rest. Adjustment controls one of the angles of the elbow. An angle of zero means the arm rest is parallel to the ground.

RightArmRestRollAngle:
The adjustable angle of the roll of the right arm rest. Adjustment controls the roll angle of the lower arm. An angle of zero means the arm rest is parallel to the ground.

HandGripsPresence:
Whether the hand grips are inserted into the backrest or not. If hand grips are present, it is implicit that the patient is intended to grip the hand grips with their hands.

ShinRest:
A fixation device that immobilizes the patients shins by the natural weight and pressure of the shins against the device.

HeelStop:
A fixation device that immobilizes the heels of the patient in counterpoint to the shin rest.

HandGrips:
A fixation device placed above the patients shoulders along the back rest, such that when gripped, ensures that the patients arms and elbows are lifted and not obstructing lateral access to the chest or breasts.

SeatPan:
A fixation device that supports the thighs (and bottom) of the patient. The seat pan is distinct from the backrest.

PatternEvent:
Classification of a Waveform annotation as a pattern.

EegAnnotation:
Classification of a Waveform annotation as belonging to EEG.

EmgAnnotation:
Classification of a Waveform annotation as belonging to ECG.

EogAnnotation:
Classification of a Waveform annotation as belonging to EOG.

Device-relatedAndEnvironment-relatedEvent:
Classification of a Waveform annotation as an event, which occurred in the recording device or in the environment (e.g. the room).

PatientConsciousness:
Classification of a Waveform annotation as a description of the patients consciousness.

EcgAnnotation:
Classification of a Waveform annotation as belonging to ECG.

NeurophysiologyRecordingAnnotations:
A Waveform annotation report comprising neurophysiology annotations added during recording.

NeurophysiologyPost-hocReviewAnnotations:
A Waveform annotation report containing neurophysiology annotations resulting from post-hoc review.

NeurophysiologyAutomatedAnalysisAnnotations:
A Waveform annotation report containing neurophysiology annotations resulting from automated analysis.

WaveformAnnotations:
A container that groups waveform annotations.

ProcedureAnnotated:
The neurophysiology or cardiology procedure to which annotations apply.

WaveformAnnotationGroup:
A container that groups a set of associated waveform annotations.

WaveformAnnotationGroupNumber:
A number identifying a set of associated annotations.

WaveformAnnotationGroupLabel:
A text describing a set of associated annotations.

WaveformAnnotationModifier:
Coded modifier for a coded waveform annotation.

AnnotationNote:
A free text information.

WaveformLibrary:
A container that references properties of involved waveforms

WaveformLibraryGroup:
A container that groups common information about a set of involved waveforms

concept.display: Waveform Library Entry Multiplex Group Descriptors
concept.definition:
WaveformLibraryEntryMultiplexGroupDescriptors:
A container that groups common information about a waveform multiplex group comprising a set of recording channel

MultiplexGroupNumber:
Identifying number of a waveform multiplex group

MultiplexGroupUid:
Unique identifier of a waveform multiplex group

SamplingFrequency:
Frequency of waveform digitalization

NumberOfChannels:
Number of channels in a waveform multiplex group

AcquisitionDatetime:
Date and Time of an Acquisition

SynchronizationFrameOfReferenceUid:
UID of common synchronization environment.

LineNoiseArtifact:
50 Hz or 60 Hz line noise artifact from a power supply

VideoRecordingOn:
Video recording turned on automatically or by the operator

VideoRecordingOff:
Video recording turned off automatically or by the operator

PreamplifierConnected:
Machine code for when the preamplifier (the headbox in case of EEG recordings) is connected to the recording device.

PreamplifierDisconnected:
Machine code for when preamplifier (the headbox in case of EEG recordings) is disconnected.

BreakoutBoxConnected:
A breakout box was connected or reconnected.
retired

BreakoutBoxDisconnected:
A breakout box was disconnected.
retired

EventButtonPressed:
The event button was pressed for the purpose of capturing an event.
retired

EventButtonTest:
The event button was pressed for the purpose of testing.
retired

TapTestBegin:
A tap test has started.
retired

TapTestEnd:
A tap test has finished.
retired

FollicleCountGroup:
The counted group of follicles that fall within a specified type and size range.

DiameterRangeMinimumValue:
The lowest value that is included in a diameter range.

DiameterRangeMaximumValue:
The highest value that is included in a diameter range.

VolumeRangeMinimumValue:
The lowest value that is included in a volume range.

VolumeRangeMaximumValue:
The highest value that is included in a volume range.

NumberOfFolliclesInRange:
The number of follicles observed in a specified size range.

TotalAntralFollicleCount:
The total number of antral follicles counted in both ovaries.

FollicleType:
The type of ovarian follicle as determined by its developmental stage.

DominantFollicle:
An antral follicle that has grown to dominate its neighboring follicles which then undergo atresia. Typically, only one or two antral follicles will become dominant in each cycle and mature to ovulation.
retired

AntralFollicle:
An ovarian follicle that has progressed from the secondary stage and has developed a small fluid-filled cavity called the antrum. Antral Follicles are also referred to as Tertiary Follicles or Graafian Follicles.

SecondaryFollicle:
An ovarian follicle that has progressed from the primary stage and has added theca cells.

PrimaryFollicle:
An ovarian follicle that has been activated from the primordial stage.

PrimordialFollicle:
An ovarian follicle that is quiescent in its original state.

FollicleCountGroupIdentifier:
The identifier of a referenced follicle count group.

DiceSimilarityCoefficient:
A measure of the pair-wise overlap of two sets defined as two times the intersection of the two samples, divided by the sum of the two samples. Also known as the SrensenDice coefficient. The samples may be points representing pixels or voxels in a geometric region.
retired

JaccardIndex:
A measure of the pair-wise overlap of two samples defined as the intersection of the two regions, divided by the union of the two samples. Also known as the Intersection Over Union (IoU). The samples may be points representing pixels or voxels in a geometric region.
retired

NumberOfPixels:
A count of the number of pixels in an image or a region of an image.

NumberOfVoxels:
A count of the number of voxels in a volume.

MeanIntensityProjection:
Values are derived by mean intensity projection of acquired data.

MedianIntensityProjection:
Values are derived by median intensity projection of acquired data

SummationProjection:
Values are derived by summation of values in the projection of acquired data

VentriculoatrialTimeInterval:
Ventriculoatrial time interval (VA time), defined as the interval between the onset of ventricular systole and the onset of atrial systole.
retired

AtrioventricularTimeInterval:
Atrioventricular time interval (AV time or AVI), defined as the interval between the onset of atrial systole and the onset of ventricular systole.
retired

LeftAtrium-descendingAortaDistance:
The shortest distance (LD) between any point on the inside of the atrium wall and any point on the outside of the descending thoracic aorta wall measured in a four-chamber view of the heart.

Post-leftAtriumSpaceIndex:
Post-Left Atrium Space (PLAS) Index is the distance between the left atrium and the descending thoracic aorta divided by the diameter of the descending thoracic aorta, where both measurements are taken in the same view (thus defining the point in the descending thoracic aorta for the diameter measurement).
retired

CerebroplacentalRatio:
The pulsatility index at the middle cerebral artery of the fetus divided by the pulsatility index at the umbilical artery. Abbreviated CPR.

UmbilicocerebralRatio:
The pulsatility index at the umbilical artery divided by the pulsatility index at the middle cerebral artery of the fetus.

IvcPreloadIndex:
The ratio of the peak retrograde flow during the A-wave to the peak forward flow during the S-wave, as measured at the inferior vena cava using pulsed-wave doppler. Abbreviated a/S.
retired

IvcS/a:
The ratio of the peak forward flow during the S-wave to the peak retrograde flow during the A-wave, as measured at the inferior vena cava using pulsed-wave doppler. This is the inverse of the Preload index.

PeakVelocityIndex:
A blood flow index calculated by subtracting the peak retrograde flow during the A-wave from the peak forward flow during the S-wave, then dividing by the peak forward flow during the D-wave, i.e., (S-a)/D.
retired

DvPulsatilityIndexInVeins:
The pulsatility index measured in the ductus venosus during the full cardiac cycle in pulsed doppler mode in any view. Abbreviated PIV.

concept.display: DV Peak Velocity Index in Veins
concept.definition:
DvPeakVelocityIndexInVeins:
The peak velocity index measured in the ductus venosus during the full cardiac cycle in pulsed doppler mode in any view. Abbreviated PVIV.

RightVentricularInletLength:
The length of the right ventricle measured at end diastole in 2D mode using a method that includes the inlet portion of the chamber in any view.

LeftVentricularInletLength:
The length of the left ventricle measured at end diastole in 2D mode using a method that includes the inlet portion of the chamber in any view.

InletIncluded:
A method of measuring a cardiac chamber length that includes the inlet portion of the chamber in the length.

FreeCordLoopMethod:
A method of measuring hemodynamics in the umbilical cord by taking the measurement in a free loop of the cord. A free loop is a portion of the umbilical cord that is not attached to the fetal body or the placenta and is instead floating freely within the amniotic fluid.

DuctusArteriosusArch:
The ductal arch formed by the ductus arteriosus as it travels from its origin at the pulmonary artery to the point of entry into the descending aorta.
retired

AorticArchView:
A planar view of the heart showing the aortic valve, ascending aorta, aortic arch, descending aorta and inferior vena cava.

concept.display: Oblique short axis view at ductus arteriosus
concept.definition:
ObliqueShortAxisViewAtDuctusArteriosus:
A planar oblique short-axis view of the heart showing the pulmonary trunk (main pulmonary artery, right pulmonary artery) and the ductus arteriosus.

concept.display: Short axis view at pulmonary artery level
concept.definition:
ShortAxisViewAtPulmonaryArteryLevel:
A planar short-axis view of the heart showing the pulmonary valve, main pulmonary artery, right and left pulmonary arteries.

ThreeVesselView:
An axial planar view of the heart showing the main pulmonary artery, ascending aorta in cross-section, and superior vena cava (SVC) in cross-section. One or both branch pulmonary arteries may also be included. Abbreviated 3VV.

ThreeVesselAndTracheaView:
An axial planar view of the heart showing the trachea and the aortic and ductal arches converging to form the proximal descending thoracic aorta. Abbreviated 3VT.

LeftVentricularOutflowTractView:
An axial planar view of the heart showing the subaortic area, aortic valve, supravalvular region, and ascending aorta.

FourChamberView:
An axial planar view of the heart showing both ventricles and both atria. The view does not necessarily include the apex of the heart.

FetalCardiovascularProfile:
Report section for assessment of cardiovascular observations that evaluate fetal well-being.

HydropsFetalisScore:
A point-based assessment of abnormal fluid accumulation in fetal body areas. This is a component of the Fetal Cardiovascular Profile Score.

CardiothoracicSizeRatioScore:
A point-based assessment of heart size relative to thoracic size based on observations of the circumferences or areas. This is a component of the Fetal Cardiovascular Profile Score.

CardiacFunctionScore:
A point-based assessment of cardiac function based on observations of valve inflow and regurgitation patterns and ventricular shortening. This is a component of the Fetal Cardiovascular Profile Score.

VenousDopplerScore:
A point-based assessment of venous flow based on Doppler observations of the umbilical vein and ductus venosus. This is a component of the Fetal Cardiovascular Profile Score.

ArterialDopplerScore:
A point-based assessment of arterial flow based on Doppler observations of the umbilical artery. This is a component of the Fetal Cardiovascular Profile Score.

FetalCardiovascularProfileScore:
A point-based score that sums the scores of five component assessments of cardiovascular observations to evaluate fetal well-being according to Makikallio et al, Human fetal cardiovascular profile score and neonatal outcome in intrauterine growth restriction. Ultrasound Obstet Gynecol 2008; 31: 4854

PvVtiForward:
The velocity time integral measured in the pulmonary vein for the antegrade flow during the full cycle in pulsed doppler mode in any view. Forward flow occurs during the D-wave and the S-wave.

PvVtiReverse:
The velocity time integral measured in the pulmonary vein for the retrograde flow during the A-wave in pulsed doppler mode in any view.

PvVtir/vtifRatio:
The ratio of the retrograde velocity time integral to the antegrade velocity time integral at the pulmonary vein.

RightVentricleCardiacOutput:
The volume rate of blood output by the right ventricle derived from the right ventricle stroke volume and heart rate. Abbreviated RVCO.

CombinedCardiacOutput:
The volume rate of blood output by the heart derived from the cardiac output of the left and right ventricles. Abbreviated CCO.

MitralValveAnnulusDiameter:
The diameter of the annulus of the mitral valve measured during diastole in 2D mode in a short axis view at the level of the mitral valve.

TricuspidValveAnnulusDiameter:
The diameter of the annulus of the tricuspid valve measured during diastole in 2D mode in a short axis view at the level of the mitral valve.

IvcS-wavePeakVelocity:
The peak velocity measured in the inferior vena cava during the S-wave in pulsed doppler mode in any view.

IvcA-wavePeakVelocity:
The peak velocity measured in the inferior vena cava during the a-wave in pulsed doppler mode in any view.

Pre-proceduralStructuralHeartMeasurementReport:
A report containing the quantitative results of human, or machine analysis of imaging acquired prior to a transcatheter structural heart procedure, focusing on measurements used to guide procedural planning and device selection.

Intra-proceduralStructuralHeartMeasurementReport:
A report containing the quantitative results of human, or machine analysis of imaging acquired during a transcatheter structural heart procedure, focusing on real-time measurements to guide procedural execution and assess immediate outcomes.

Post-proceduralStructuralHeartMeasurementReport:
A report containing the quantitative results of human, or machine analysis of imaging acquired after a transcatheter structural heart procedure, focusing on the evaluation of procedural success, device placement, and patient outcomes.

Mid-esophageal0DegreeTee:
A mid-esophageal view directed anteriorly with the transesophageal transducer in its baseline orientation.

Mid-esophageal45DegreeTee:
A mid-esophageal plane directed 45 degrees clockwise from the mid-esophageal 0 degree TEE.

Mid-esophageal60DegreeTee:
A mid-esophageal plane directed 60 degrees clockwise from the mid-esophageal 0 degree TEE.

Mid-esophageal90DegreeTee:
A mid-esophageal plane directed 90 degrees clockwise from the mid-esophageal 0 degree TEE.

Mid-esophageal135DegreeTee:
A mid-esophageal plane directed 135 degrees clockwise from the mid-esophageal 0 degree TEE.

concept.display: Ball and disk type left atrial appendage closure device
concept.definition:
BallAndDiskTypeLeftAtrialAppendageClosureDevice:
A device, in the form of a disk and cylindrical lobe connected by a central waist, for sealing off a left atrium appendage.

concept.display: Ball type left atrial appendage closure device
concept.definition:
BallTypeLeftAtrialAppendageClosureDevice:
A spherical device for sealing off a left atrium appendage.

LeftAtrialAppendageClosureDevice:
A device for sealing off a left atrium appendage.

OstiumOfLeftAuricularAppendage:
The anatomical orifice connecting the left atrial appendage to the left atrium of the heart.

TransseptalPunctureHeight:
The distance from the mitral leaflets to the level of the transseptal puncture measured during systole in a four-chamber view, with the measurement line drawn parallel to the atrial septum.

AortaSinotubularJunctionArea:
The cross-sectional area of the ascending aorta measured between the aortic sinuses of Valsalva and normal tubular configuration of the aorta during diastole in 2D or 3D, in the long axis view.

AorticAnnulusCalcificationSeverity:
The qualitative severity of calcification of the annulus of the aortic valve, evaluated during systole, in any view at the level of the annulus of the aortic valve.

AorticAnnulusMaxDiameter:
The widest diameter of the annulus of the aortic valve measured at systole, in a short axis view at the level of the annulus of the aortic valve.

AorticAnnulusMinDiameter:
The narrowest diameter of the annulus of the aortic valve measured at systole, in a short axis view at the level of the annulus of the aortic valve.

AorticAnnulusPerimeter:
The length of the perimeter of the annulus of the aortic valve measured at systole, in a short axis view at the level of the annulus of the aortic valve.

AorticCalcificationVolume:
The volume of calcification of the annulus of the aortic valve, evaluated during systole, in a short axis view at the level of the annulus of the aortic valve, using a qualitative method.

AorticCommissuresCalcificationSeverity:
The qualitative severity of calcification of the commissures of the aortic valve, evaluated at any time during the cardiac cycle, in any view at the level of the annulus of the aortic valve.

AorticRootHeight:
The distance from the aortic annulus to the sinotubular junction measured during diastole in the long axis view.

AorticSinotubularJunctionDiameter:
The diameter of the ascending aorta measured at the level of the sinotubular junction during diastole, in any view.

AorticSinusOfValsalvaArea:
The area within the sinus of valsalva measured during diastole, in a short axis view, at the level of the sinus of valsalva.

AorticValveCoaptationLength:
The length of coaptation (where the aortic valve leaflets are in contact), measured during diastole in the long axis view.

concept.display: Aortic valve noncoronary leaflet intercommissural angle
concept.definition:
AorticValveNoncoronaryLeafletIntercommissuralAngle:
The angle between the two commissures of the noncoronary leaflet of the aortic valve measured during diastole, in a short axis view at the level of the aortic valve.

concept.display: Aortic valve right leaflet intercommissural angle
concept.definition:
AorticValveRightLeafletIntercommissuralAngle:
The angle between the two commissures of the right leaflet of the aortic valve measured during diastole, in a short axis view at the level of the aortic valve.

concept.display: Aortic valve left leaflet intercommissural angle
concept.definition:
AorticValveLeftLeafletIntercommissuralAngle:
The angle between the two commissures of the left leaflet of the aortic valve measured during diastole, in a short axis view at the level of the aortic valve.

concept.display: Aortic valve noncoronary leaflet intercommissural distance
concept.definition:
AorticValveNoncoronaryLeafletIntercommissuralDistance:
The straight-line distance between the two commissures of the left leaflet of the aortic valve measured during diastole, in a short axis view at the level of the aortic valve.

concept.display: Aortic valve right leaflet intercommissural distance
concept.definition:
AorticValveRightLeafletIntercommissuralDistance:
The straight-line distance between the two commissures of the right leaflet of the aortic valve measured during diastole, in a short axis view at the level of the aortic valve.

concept.display: Aortic valve left leaflet intercommissural distance
concept.definition:
AorticValveLeftLeafletIntercommissuralDistance:
The straight-line distance between the two commissures of the left leaflet of the aortic valve measured during diastole, in a short axis view at the level of the aortic valve.

concept.display: Aortic valve left coronary leaflet height
concept.definition:
AorticValveLeftCoronaryLeafletHeight:
The perpendicular distance from the plane of the annulus to the tip of the left coronary leaflet measured during diastole, in a long axis view.

concept.display: Aortic valve left coronary leaflet length
concept.definition:
AorticValveLeftCoronaryLeafletLength:
The distance along the surface of the left coronary leaflet from the tip to the hinge point of the leaflet to the aortic annulus, measured during diastole, in a long axis view.

AorticValveNoncoronaryLeafletHeight:
The perpendicular distance from the plane of the annulus to the tip of the noncoronary leaflet measured during diastole, in a long axis view.

AorticValveNoncoronaryLeafletLength:
The distance along the surface of the noncoronary leaflet from the tip to the hinge point of the leaflet to the aortic annulus, measured during diastole, in a long axis view.

concept.display: Aortic valve right coronary leaflet height
concept.definition:
AorticValveRightCoronaryLeafletHeight:
The perpendicular distance from the plane of the annulus to the tip of the right coronary leaflet measured during diastole, in a long axis view.

concept.display: Aortic valve right coronary leaflet length
concept.definition:
AorticValveRightCoronaryLeafletLength:
The distance along the surface of the right coronary leaflet from the tip to the hinge point of the leaflet to the aortic annulus, measured during diastole, in a long axis view.

AscendingAortaDiameter:
The diameter within the ascending aorta measured during diastole in 2D, in any view at the level of the right pulmonary artery.

LeftMainCoronaryOstiumHeight:
The distance between the aortic annulus and the left main coronary ostium measured at their closest points, during systole, in a long axis view.

concept.display: Left ventricular outflow tract calcification severity
concept.definition:
LeftVentricularOutflowTractCalcificationSeverity:
The qualitative severity of calcification of the left ventricular outflow tract, from the annular plane to 5 mm below, evaluated at any time during the cardiac cycle and in any view.

MaximumAorticPlaqueThickness:
The maximum thickness of the largest atherosclerotic plaque deposit found within the ascending aorta, measured during systole, in the view that demonstrates the thickest plaque, using any appropriate imaging method

RightCoronaryArteryOstiumHeight:
The distance between the aortic annulus and the right main coronary ostium measured at their closest points, during systole, in a long axis view.

RightVentricleDiastolicMajorAxis:
The internal longitudinal length of the right ventricle from the apex to the tricuspid annulus, measured during diastole, in a four-chamber view.

concept.display: Right ventricular diastolic mid segment minor axis
concept.definition:
RightVentricularDiastolicMidSegmentMinorAxis:
The internal diameter of the right ventricle from the interventricular septum to the free wall, measured at the level of the papillary muscles during diastole, in a four-chamber view.

concept.display: Right ventricular diastolic basal minor axis
concept.definition:
RightVentricularDiastolicBasalMinorAxis:
The internal diameter of the right ventricle from the interventricular septum to the free wall, measured in the basal third of the right ventricle during diastole, in a four-chamber view.

concept.display: Mitral anterior leaflet A1 scallop length
concept.definition:
MitralAnteriorLeafletA1ScallopLength:
The distance along the hinge line of the A1 scallop of the anterior leaflet of the mitral valve, measured during systole, in the long axis view.

concept.display: Mitral anterior leaflet A2 scallop length
concept.definition:
MitralAnteriorLeafletA2ScallopLength:
The distance along the hinge line of the A2 scallop of the anterior leaflet of the mitral valve, measured during systole, in the long axis view.

concept.display: Mitral anterior leaflet A3 scallop length
concept.definition:
MitralAnteriorLeafletA3ScallopLength:
The distance along the hinge line of the A3 scallop of the anterior leaflet of the mitral valve, measured during systole, in the long axis view.

MitralAnteriorLeafletArea:
The area of the atrial surface of the anterior leaflet of the mitral valve measured during systole, in a 3D en face view of the mitral valve.

Aorto-mitralInterAnnularAngle:
The angle between the plane passing through the aortic annulus and the plane passing through the mitral annulus measured during systole, in the long axis view.

MitralCommissureDistance:
The straight-line distance between the two commissures of the anterior and posterior leaflets of the mitral valve measured during diastole, in a two-chamber view.

MitralTrigone-to-trigoneDistance:
The straight-line distance between a point in the right trigone region of the mitral annulus and a point in the left trigone region of the mitral annulus, measured during systole, in a 3D en face view of the mitral valve.

MitralAnnularExcursion:
The longitudinal displacement of the plane of the mitral annulus over the course of a cardiac cycle, measured any view.

concept.display: Mitral annulus anterolateral to posteromedial diameter
concept.definition:
MitralAnnulusAnterolateralToPosteromedialDiameter:
The diameter of the annulus of the mitral valve measured from the anterolateral aspect to the posteromedial aspect, during systole, in a 3D en face view of the mitral valve.

MitralAnnulusAnteroposteriorDiameter:
The diameter of the annulus of the mitral valve measured from the anterior aspect to the posterior aspect, during systole, in the short axis view at the level of the mitral annulus.

MitralAnnulusArea:
The area within the annulus of the mitral valve measured during systole, in a short axis view at the level of the annulus of the mitral valve.

MitralAnnulusCalcificationSeverity:
The qualitative severity of calcification of the annulus of the mitral valve, evaluated during diastole, in any view, at the level of the annulus of the mitral valve.

MitralAnnulusCommissuralDiameter:
The diameter of the annulus of the mitral valve at the level of the commissures of the annulus, measured during systole, in a 3D en face view of the mitral valve.

MitralAnnulusDiameterRatio:
The ratio of the anteroposterior diameter of the mitral annulus and the anterolateral diameter of the mitral annulus, measured during systole.

MitralAnnulusHeight:
The sum of the vertical distance from the highest point on the mitral annulus to the mitral annular plane and the vertical distance from the lowest point on the mitral annulus to the mitral annular plane. It is measured at systole, in a 3D transverse view of the mitral valve.

MitralAnnulusNonplanarityAngle:
The angle between a vector from the furthest anterior aspect of the annulus to the midpoint of the commissural diameter and a vector from the furthest posterior aspect of the annulus to the midpoint of the commissural diameter. It is measured at systole, in a 3D view of the mitral valve.

MitralAnnulusPerimeter:
The length of the perimeter of the annulus of the mitral valve measured during systole, in a short axis view at the level of the annulus of the mitral valve.

MitralValveCoaptationLength:
The length of coaptation (where the anterior and posterior leaflets are in contact) of the mitral valve, measured during systole, in a 3D view.

MitralValveInterpapillaryDistance:
The distance between the two papillary muscle tips of the mitral valve, measured during diastole in a four-chamber view.

concept.display: Anterolateral papillary muscle to the left trigone
concept.definition:
AnterolateralPapillaryMuscleToTheLeftTrigone:
The distance between the anterolateral papillary muscle tip and a point in the left trigone region of the mitral annulus, measured during systole in a four-chamber view.

concept.display: Posteromedial papillary muscle to the right trigone
concept.definition:
PosteromedialPapillaryMuscleToTheRightTrigone:
The distance between the posteromedial papillary muscle tip and a point in the right trigone region of the mitral annulus, measured during systole in a four-chamber view.

MitralValveProlapseArea:
The surface area of the portion of the mitral valve leaflets that is displaced above the annular plane (prolapsed) measured during systole, in a short axis view.

MitralValveProlapseVolume:
The volume encompassed by annular plane and the portion of the mitral valve leaflets that is displaced above the annular plane (prolapsed) measured during systole, in a short axis view.

MitralValveSegmentFlailGap:
The distance between the tip of the free edge of a flail mitral valve leaflet or segment and the plane of the mitral annulus measured during systole, in any view.

MitralValveSphericityIndex:
The ratio of the transverse diameter of the left ventricle at the level of the papillary muscle base divided by the longitudinal distance between the level of the papillary muscle base and the mitral annulus plane, measured at diastole in a four-chamber view. See

MitralValveTentingHeight:
The perpendicular distance from the point of coaptation (where the anterior and posterior leaflets of the mitral valve meet) to the annular plane measured during systole, in a 3D or 2D view at the level of the mitral annulus.

MitralValveTentingArea:
The area between the ventricular surface of the leaflets of the mitral valve and the annular plane measured during systole, in a 3D view at the level of the mitral annulus.

concept.display: Mitral valve tenting segment height A1-P1
concept.definition:
MitralValveTentingSegmentHeightA1-p1:
The distance from the point where the A1-P1 scallops of the mitral valve contact (coaptation point) to the annular plane measured during systole, in a four-chamber view at the level of the mitral annulus.

concept.display: Mitral valve tenting segment height A2-P2
concept.definition:
MitralValveTentingSegmentHeightA2-p2:
The distance from the point where the A2-P2 scallops of the mitral valve contact (coaptation point) to the annular plane measured during systole, in a four-chamber view at the level of the mitral annulus.

concept.display: Mitral valve tenting segment height A3-P3
concept.definition:
MitralValveTentingSegmentHeightA3-p3:
The distance from the point where the A3-P3 scallops of the mitral valve contact (coaptation point) to the annular plane measured during systole, in a four-chamber view at the level of the mitral annulus.

PosteriorMitralValveLeafletArea:
The combined area of the P1, P2 and P3 leaflet scallops of the posterior mitral valve, measured during systole, in the long axis view.

PosteriorMitralValveLeafletLength:
The distance along the hinge line of the posterior mitral valve P1, P2 and P3 leaflet scallops measured during systole, in the long axis view.

concept.display: Posterior mitral valve P1 leaflet scallop length
concept.definition:
PosteriorMitralValveP1LeafletScallopLength:
The distance along the hinge line of the posterior mitral valve P1 leaflet scallop during systole, in the long axis view.

concept.display: Posterior mitral valve P2 leaflet scallop length
concept.definition:
PosteriorMitralValveP2LeafletScallopLength:
The distance along the hinge line of the posterior mitral valve P2 leaflet scallop during systole, in the long axis view.

concept.display: Posterior mitral valve P3 leaflet scallop length
concept.definition:
PosteriorMitralValveP3LeafletScallopLength:
The distance along the hinge line of the posterior mitral valve P3 leaflet scallop during systole, in the long axis view.

TricuspidAnnulusArea:
The area within the annulus of the tricuspid valve measured during diastole, in a 3D en face view of the tricuspid valve.

concept.display: Tricuspid annulus area diastolic systolic ratio
concept.definition:
TricuspidAnnulusAreaDiastolicSystolicRatio:
The area within the annulus of the tricuspid valve calculated at diastole divided by the area within the annulus of the tricuspid valve calculated at systole, in a 3D en face view of the tricuspid valve.

TricuspidAnnulusPerimeter:
The length of the perimeter of the annulus of the tricuspid valve measured during diastole, in a four-chamber view.

TricuspidValveCoaptationLength:
The length of coaptation (where the anterior, posterior, and septal leaflets are in contact), measured during systole, in a 3D view.

TricuspidValveMajorAxisDiastole:
The maximum diameter of the annulus of the tricuspid valve measured during diastole, in a four-chamber view.

TricuspidValveMinorAxis:
The minimum diameter of the annulus of the tricuspid valve measured during diastole, in a four-chamber view.

TricuspidValveSphericityIndex:
The ratio of the maximum diameter of the annulus of the tricuspid valve and the minimum diameter of the annulus of the tricuspid valve, measured during diastole, in a four-chamber view.

TricuspidValveTentingHeight:
The distance from the point where the leaflets of the tricuspid valve contact (coaptation point) to the annular plane measured during systole, in a four-chamber 3D transverse view of the tricuspid valve.

TricuspidValveTentingVolume:
The volume of the region between atrial surface of the leaflets and the annular plane measured during systole, in a 3D view of the tricuspid valve.

concept.display: Left atrial appendage closure device circumference
concept.definition:
LeftAtrialAppendageClosureDeviceCircumference:
The circumference of the left atrial appendage closure device after deployment, measured at the shoulder during end-systole in a 2D or 3D view of the left atrial appendage.

concept.display: Left atrial appendage closure device compression ratio
concept.definition:
LeftAtrialAppendageClosureDeviceCompressionRatio:
The ratio of the diameter of the left atrial appendage closure device after deployment, measured at the shoulder during end-systole in a 2D or 3D view of the left atrial appendage, and diameter of the left atrial appendage closure device as specified by its manufacturer.

concept.display: Left atrial appendage closure device diameter
concept.definition:
LeftAtrialAppendageClosureDeviceDiameter:
The diameter of the left atrial appendage closure device after deployment, measured at the shoulder during end-systole in a 2D view of the left atrial appendage.

concept.display: Left atrial appendage closure device size
concept.definition:
LeftAtrialAppendageClosureDeviceSize:
The diameter of the left atrial appendage closure device as specified by its manufacturer.

LeftAtrialAppendageDepth:
The maximum distance from the left atrial appendage orifice (the plane between the left upper pulmonary vein ridge and the left circumflex artery), to the most distal point of the left atrial appendage cavity, measured during end-diastole in a 2D view of the left atrial appendage.

concept.display: Left atrial appendage landing zone major axis
concept.definition:
LeftAtrialAppendageLandingZoneMajorAxis:
The maximum diameter of the left atrial appendage measured 1cm to 1.5cm inferior to the orifice (the plane between the left upper pulmonary vein ridge and the left circumflex artery), during end-systole, in a 2D view of the left atrial appendage.

LeftAtrialAppendageMajorAxis:
The maximum diameter of the left atrial appendage orifice (the plane between the left upper pulmonary vein ridge and the left circumflex artery), measured during end-systole, in a 2D view of the left atrial appendage.

LeftAtrialAppendageMinorAxis:
The minimum diameter of the left atrial appendage orifice (the plane between the left upper pulmonary vein ridge and the left circumflex artery), measured during end-systole, in a 2D view of the left atrial appendage.

LeftAtrialAppendageOstiumPerimeter:
The perimeter of the left atrial appendage orifice (the plane between the left upper pulmonary vein ridge and the left circumflex artery), measured during end-systole, in a 3D en face view of the left atrial appendage.

EndothelialCellCountKeyMeasurements:

OphthalmicImageRoiMeasurements:
Measurements of Ophthalmic Images based on a Region of Interest.

RepositionedRoiOrGrid:
Indicator that measurements were made with ROI or grid positioned differently than used for a prior measurement set.

concept.display: Visual Field Global Deviation from Normal
concept.definition:
VisualFieldGlobalDeviationFromNormal:
Weighted average deviation from the age corrected normal visual field, as decibel. Corresponds to Global Deviation from Normal (0024,0066) in the Results Normals Sequence (0024,0064).
retired

concept.display: Visual Field Localized Deviation From Normal
concept.definition:
VisualFieldLocalizedDeviationFromNormal:
Weighted square root of loss variance in visual field, as decibel. Corresponds to Localized Deviation From Normal (0024,0068) in the Results Normals Sequence (0024,0064).
retired

FixationFalsePositiveRatio:
The ratio between the number of times patient responses occurred when no visual stimulus was present (false positive responses) and the number of trials presented. Corresponds to ratio of False Positives Quantity (0024,0060) to Positive Catch Trials Quantity (0024,0056) in the Visual Field Catch Trial Sequence (0024,0034).
retired

FixationFalsePositivePercent:
Estimated percentage of all patient responses that occurred at a time when no visual stimulus was present (false positive responses) , as percent. Corresponds to False Positives Estimate (0024,0054) in the Visual Field Catch Trial Sequence (0024,0034).
retired

FixationFalseNegativeRatio:
The ratio between the number of times stimuli were not seen by the patient but were previously seen at a lower luminance earlier in the visual field test (false negative responses) and the number of trials presented. Corresponds to ratio of False Negatives Quantity (0024,0050) to Negative Catch Trials Quantity (0024,0048) in the Visual Field Catch Trial Sequence (0024,0034).
retired

FixationFalseNegativePercent:
Estimated percentage of all stimuli that were not seen by the patient but were previously seen at a lower luminance earlier in the visual field test (false negative responses) , as percent. Corresponds to False Negatives Estimate (0024,0046) in the Visual Field Catch Trial Sequence (0024,0034).
retired

FixationLossesRatio:
The ratio between the number of times a patient loses visual fixation while maintaining a visual gaze on a single location and the number of trials presented. Corresponds to ratio of Patient Not Properly Fixated Quantity (0024,0036) to Fixation Checked Quantity (0024,0035) in Fixation Sequence (0024,0032).
retired

AverageMacularThickness:
Average macular thickness across all ETDRS subfields.
retired

CupToDiscAreaRatio:
Ratio of the optic cup area to the optic disc area.
retired

CupToDiscRatioVertical:
Ratio of the vertical diameter of the optic cup to that of the vertical diameter of the optic disc.
retired

CupToDiscRatioHorizontal:
Ratio of the horizontal diameter of the optic cup to that of the horizontal diameter of the optic disc.
retired

NeuroretinalRimArea:
Area of the neuroretinal rim portion of the optic nerve head, or Bruch's Membrane Opening-based Minimum Rim Area (BMO-MRA).
retired

NeuroretinalRimWidth:
Average width of the neuroretinal rim portion of the optic nerve head, or Bruch's Membrane Opening-based Minimum Rim Width (BMO-MRW).
retired

OpticCupArea:
Area of the cup portion of the optic nerve head.
retired

OpticDiscArea:
Area of the optic disc or Bruch's Membrane Opening (BMO).
retired

OpticCupVolume:
Volume of the cup portion of the optic nerve head.
retired

RnflAverageThickness:
Average measured thickness of the retinal nerve fiber layer (RNFL) , i.e., the distance between the internal limiting membrane (ILM) and the Gangion Cell Layer (GCL) , across the entire ROI (also denoted as the global RNFL thickness).
retired

RnflInferiorSectorThickness:
Average measured thickness of the retinal nerve fiber layer (RNFL) , i.e., the distance between the internal limiting membrane (ILM) and the Gangion Cell Layer (GCL) , in the inferior sector as defined by the measurement method.
retired

RnflSuperiorSectorThickness:
Average measured thickness of the retinal nerve fiber layer (RNFL) , i.e., the distance between the internal limiting membrane (ILM) and the Gangion Cell Layer (GCL) , in the superior sector as defined by the measurement method.
retired

RnflTemporalSectorThickness:
Average measured thickness of the retinal nerve fiber layer (RNFL) , i.e., the distance between the internal limiting membrane (ILM) and the Gangion Cell Layer (GCL) , in the temporal sector as defined by the measurement method.
retired

RnflNasalSectorThickness:
Average measured thickness of the retinal nerve fiber layer (RNFL) , i.e., the distance between the internal limiting membrane (ILM) and the Gangion Cell Layer (GCL) , in the nasal sector as defined by the measurement method.
retired

RnflNasal-superiorSectorThickness:
Average measured thickness of the retinal nerve fiber layer (RNFL) , i.e., the distance between the internal limiting membrane (ILM) and the Gangion Cell Layer (GCL) , in the nasal-superior sector as defined by the measurement method.
retired

RnflNasal-inferiorSectorThickness:
Average measured thickness of the retinal nerve fiber layer (RNFL) , i.e., the distance between the internal limiting membrane (ILM) and the Gangion Cell Layer (GCL) , in the nasal-inferior sector as defined by the measurement method.
retired

RnflTemporal-inferiorSectorThickness:
Average measured thickness of the retinal nerve fiber layer (RNFL) , i.e., the distance between the internal limiting membrane (ILM) and the Gangion Cell Layer (GCL) , in the temporal-inferior sector as defined by the measurement method.
retired

RnflTemporal-superiorSectorThickness:
Average measured thickness of the retinal nerve fiber layer (RNFL) , i.e., the distance between the internal limiting membrane (ILM) and the Gangion Cell Layer (GCL) , in the temporal-superior sector as defined by the measurement method.
retired

RetinalNerveFiberLayerSymmetry:
Ratio of the global retinal nerve fiber layer (RNFL) thickness measurement of the right eye to that of the left eye.
retired

RetinalRoiWidth:
Region of interest circular area diameter, eliptical area major axis, or rectangular area major dimension, used for measurement of retinal layer thicknesses.
retired

RetinalRoiHeight:
Region of interest eliptical area minor axis, or rectangular area minor dimension, used for measurement of retinal layer thicknesses.
retired

RnflClockfacePosition1Thickness:
Retinal nerve fiber layer thickness at clockface position 1, in the clockwise direction for the right eye and the counter-clockwise direction for the left eye, as viewed from an anterior position. This is in the nasal superior quadrant.
retired

RnflClockfacePosition2Thickness:
Retinal nerve fiber layer thickness at clockface position 2, in the clockwise direction for the right eye and the counter-clockwise direction for the left eye, as viewed from an anterior position. This is in the nasal superior quadrant.
retired

RnflClockfacePosition3Thickness:
Retinal nerve fiber layer thickness at clockface position 3, in the clockwise direction for the right eye and the counter-clockwise direction for the left eye, as viewed from an anterior position. This is the nasal position.
retired

RnflClockfacePosition4Thickness:
Retinal nerve fiber layer thickness at clockface position 4, in the clockwise direction for the right eye and the counter-clockwise direction for the left eye, as viewed from an anterior position. This is in the nasal inferior quadrant.
retired

RnflClockfacePosition5Thickness:
Retinal nerve fiber layer thickness at clockface position 5, in the clockwise direction for the right eye and the counter-clockwise direction for the left eye, as viewed from an anterior position. This is in the nasal inferior quadrant.
retired

RnflClockfacePosition6Thickness:
Retinal nerve fiber layer thickness at clockface position 6. This is the inferior position.
retired

RnflClockfacePosition7Thickness:
Retinal nerve fiber layer thickness at clockface position 7, in the clockwise direction for the right eye and the counter-clockwise direction for the left eye, as viewed from an anterior position. This is in the temporal inferior quadrant.
retired

RnflClockfacePosition8Thickness:
Retinal nerve fiber layer thickness at clockface position 8, in the clockwise direction for the right eye and the counter-clockwise direction for the left eye, as viewed from an anterior position. This is in the temporal inferior quadrant.
retired

RnflClockfacePosition9Thickness:
Retinal nerve fiber layer thickness at clockface position 9, in the clockwise direction for the right eye and the counter-clockwise direction for the left eye, as viewed from an anterior position. This is the temporal position.
retired

RnflClockfacePosition10Thickness:
Retinal nerve fiber layer thickness at clockface position 10, in the clockwise direction for the right eye and the counter-clockwise direction for the left eye, as viewed from an anterior position. This is in the temporal superior quadrant.
retired

RnflClockfacePosition11Thickness:
Retinal nerve fiber layer thickness at clockface position 11, in the clockwise direction for the right eye and the counter-clockwise direction for the left eye, as viewed from an anterior position. This is in the temporal superior quadrant.
retired

RnflClockfacePosition12Thickness:
Retinal nerve fiber layer thickness at clockface position 12. This is the superior position.
retired

AverageGanglionCellThickness:
Average thickness of the ganglion cell layer across the entire ROI (also denoted as the global GCL thickness).

MinimumGanglionCellThickness:
Minimum thickness of the ganglion cell layer over a single meridian crossing the annulus.

AverageGanglionCellThicknessSuperiorSector:
Average ganglion cell thickness in the superior sector as defined by the measurement method.

AverageGanglionCellThicknessNasal-superiorSector:
Average ganglion cell thickness in the nasal-superior sector as defined by the measurement method.

AverageGanglionCellThicknessNasalSector:
Average ganglion cell thickness in the nasal sector as defined by the measurement method.

AverageGanglionCellThicknessNasal-inferiorSector:
Average ganglion cell thickness in the nasal-inferior sector as defined by the measurement method.

AverageGanglionCellThicknessInferiorSector:

AverageGanglionCellThicknessTemporal-inferiorSector:
Average ganglion cell thickness in the temporal-inferior as defined by the measurement method.

concept.display: Average ganglion cell thickness temporal sector

AverageGanglionCellThicknessTemporalSector:
Average ganglion cell thickness in the temporal sector as defined by the measurement method.

concept.display: Average ganglion cell thickness temporal-superior sector
concept.definition:
AverageGanglionCellThicknessTemporal-superiorSector:
Average ganglion cell thickness in the temporal-superior sector as defined by the measurement method.

concept.display: Average ganglion cell thickness in posterior pole grid
concept.definition:
AverageGanglionCellThicknessInPosteriorPoleGrid:
Average ganglion cell thickness in the posterior pole grid, as a table of values.

concept.display: Ganglion cell and inner plexiform layers
concept.definition:
GanglionCellAndInnerPlexiformLayers:
Anatomic region including the ganglion cell layer (GCL) and the inner plexiform layer (IPL).
retired

GanglionCellComplex:
Anatomic region including the Ganglion cell layer (GCL) , the inner plexiform layer (IPL) , and the retinal nerve fiber layer (RNFL).
retired

SemicircularSectors:
Measurement method on a circular ROI with four overlapping 180 semicircular sectors centered on vertical and horizontal axes (superior, inferior, nasal, temporal).

QuadrantSectors:
Measurement method on a circular ROI with four 90 sectors centered on vertical and horizontal axes (superior, inferior, nasal, temporal).
retired

SnitRectangularSectors:
Measurement method on a rectangular ROI with four overlapping rectangular sectors (superior, nasal, inferior, temporal).
retired

EllipticalAnnulusSectors:
Measurement method on an elliptical annulus ROI, divided into six 60 sectors with boundaries beginning at 30 from vertical (superior, nasal-superior, nasal-inferior, inferior, temporal-inferior, temporal-superior). The outer ellipse of the annulus has a minor axis diameter equal to the Retinal ROI height and is aligned vertically, and a major axis diameter equal to the Retinal ROI width aligned horizontally. The dimensions of the inner ellipse of the annulus, centered on the fovea, are manufacturer specific.
retired

Garway-heathSectors:
Measurement method on a circular ROI, divided into six sectors - a 110 nasal sector and a 90 temporal sector centered on the fovea-Bruch's membrane opening (BMO) axis, and four 40 sectors (temporal-superior, nasal-superior, nasal-inferior, temporal-inferior).
retired

Quadrant-octantSectors:
Measurement method on a circular ROI, divided into six sectors - 90 nasal and temporal quadrants centered on the horizontal axis, and four 45 octants (temporal-superior, nasal-superior, nasal-inferior, temporal-inferior).
retired

PosteriorPole8x8Grid:
Measurement method on a rectangular ROI, divided into an 8x8 grid positioned symmetrically to the fovea-optic disc axis and centered on the optic disc.
retired

RnflClockfaceMethod:
Measurement method on a circular ROI, centered on the optic nerve head, with twelve measurements of retinal nerve fiber layer thickness made at 30 intervals on the circumference.
